s":["Welsh: from <i>fychan</i>, a lenited form of <i>bychan</i>, a diminutive of <i>bach</i> ‘little’. This was often used to distinguish the younger of two bearers of the same personal name, typically the son of a father with the same name."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret von Vianden was born about 1282, in France, her father, Heinrich von Vianden, was 36 and her mother, Beatrice De Houffalize, was 31. She married Jacques Jacquemin De Fayolles Rumigny after 1298. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"Abt 1282–":"umbes 1282–Surnud","1282–Female":"1282–Surnud","1280–1327":"1280–1327","1298–1358":"1298–1358","1248–1291":"1248–1291","1252–Female":"1252–Surnud","AFT 1298":"pärast 1298","1327":"1327","1248":"1248","1358":"1358","Abt 1282":"umbes 1282","Abt 1298":"umbes 1298","1298":"1298","1252":"1252","1282":"1282","1291":"1291","1280":"1280","France":"Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"Abt 1282–":"noin 1282–Kuollut","1282–Female":"1282–Kuollut","1280–1327":"1280–1327","1298–1358":"1298–1358","1248–1291":"1248–1291","1252–Female":"1252–Kuollut","AFT 1298":"1298 jälkeen","1327":"1327","1248":"1248","1358":"1358","Abt 1282":"noin 1282","Abt 1298":"noin 1298","1298":"1298","1252":"1252","1282":"1282","1291":"1291","1280":"1280","France":"Ranska"},"fr":{"Abt 1282–":"environ 1282–Décédée","1282–Female":"1282–Décédée","1280–1327":"1280–1327","1298–1358":"1298–1358","1248–1291":"1248–1291","1252–Female":"1252–Décédée","AFT 1298":"après 1298","1327":"1327","1248":"1248","1358":"1358","Abt 1282":"environ 1282","Abt 1298":"environ 1298","1298":"1298","1252":"1252","1282":"1282","1291":"1291","1280":"1280","France":"France","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Margaret von Viand